					  <h3>RAJESH KHANNA ‚Äì ‚ÄúA soul like his doesn‚Äôt fade‚Äù</h3>

					  <p>When Rajesh Khanna spoke of Rahul Dev Burman, it never sounded like he was remembering someone who was gone. It felt more like he was calling out to a friend who had simply stepped into another room.</p>
					  <p>On Panchamda‚Äôs death anniversary, when asked to reflect, Khanna didn‚Äôt bow his head in sorrow. Instead, his eyes softened with warmth.</p>
					  <p>‚ÄúWho says R.D. Burman is no more?‚Äù he murmured. ‚ÄúA genius like him doesn‚Äôt leave us. His music keeps him alive‚Äîbright, breathing, and forever young. Every time a snappy beat or a soulful line reaches my ears, I feel him beside me.‚Äù</p>

					  <p>To Khanna, Pancham lived through every generation that rediscovered him‚Äî</p>
					  <ul>
						<li>through a revived ‚ÄúBachna Ae Haseenon,‚Äù</li>
						<li>through an old mukhda reappearing in <em>Jaane Tu Ya Jaane Na</em>,</li>
						<li>through familiar background notes hidden in <em>Main Hoon Na</em>.</li>
					  </ul>
					  <p>‚ÄúThese are his footprints,‚Äù Khanna said gently. ‚ÄúThis is how he walks with us still.‚Äù</p>

					  <p>He remembered how deeply Pancham shaped his own rise. How <em>Aradhana</em>‚Äôs ‚ÄúMere Sapnon Ki Rani,‚Äù though credited elsewhere, was truly born from Pancham‚Äôs hands. How the harmonica he adored danced through the tune, how the rhythm of a train carried two young dreamers toward a destiny neither could yet see.</p>
					  <p>‚ÄúI watched that song take its first breath,‚Äù Khanna recalled. ‚ÄúIt felt like witnessing magic.‚Äù</p>

					  <p>And then came the stories that only two close hearts could share‚ÄîPancham waking from sleep with a melody in his mind, scribbling notes lit only by a midnight lamp, finding inspiration in a honking car or the rumble of an airplane.</p>
					  <p>Once, flying together to Delhi, Pancham hummed a tune into the roar of the engines. Months later, when a song in <em>Kati Patang</em> needed a waltz-like soul, Khanna remembered it‚Äîthe tune born in the sky‚Äîand it became ‚ÄúYeh Jo Mohabbat Hai.‚Äù</p>

					  <p>Another time, in a quiet temple in Kashmir, as bells rang and prayers rose into the mountain air, Pancham stepped outside already humming a new melody. He promised Khanna he would give him that tune someday. Long after, it found its place in the jubilant ‚ÄúJai Jai Shiv Shankar.‚Äù</p>

					  <p>Khanna always defended the man behind the myth.</p>
					  <p>‚ÄúPeople said he was reclusive,‚Äù he sighed, ‚Äúbut he was simply sensitive‚Äîgentle, shy, and full of heart. He never chased the spotlight. He laughed easily, loved deeply, and lived with music as his constant companion.‚Äù</p>

					  <p>His humour echoed in ‚ÄúEk Chatur Naar.‚Äù His tenderness bloomed in ‚ÄúJaane-Jaan,‚Äù ‚ÄúChura Liya Hai Tumne,‚Äù and ‚ÄúHum Dono Do Premi.‚Äù Every song was a piece of him‚Äîunfiltered and true.</p>

					  <p>But the tale turned heavier when Khanna spoke of the years after 1991, when the industry turned away and declared his music no longer ‚Äúsaleable.‚Äù</p>
					  <p>‚ÄúIt broke him,‚Äù Khanna whispered. ‚ÄúIt broke many of us who knew him.‚Äù</p>

					  <p>Just when Pancham was ready for a glorious return‚Äîwith the breathtaking score of <em>1942: A Love Story</em>‚Äîfate, unkind as ever, took him from the world he adored.</p>

					  <p>Now, a chowk in Santacruz West bears his name‚Äîa small corner of Mumbai forever humming his memory, unveiled by Asha Bhonsle like a blessing.</p>
					  <p>But to Khanna, it was only the beginning.</p>

					  <p>‚ÄúWe need more,‚Äù he said softly.</p>
					  <p>‚ÄúMore spaces, more music, more celebrations of his fire and tenderness. Because someone like Panchamda‚Ä¶ someone who put his heartbeat into every note‚Ä¶ does not fade. He belongs not to the past, but to every moment where music still feels alive.‚Äù</p>
